{{Infobox monarch | name = Abd al-Wahid II | title = Caliph of Morocco | image = <!-- Flag of Morocco 1147 1269.svg --> | reign = 1232–1242 | father= [[Idris al-Ma'mun]] | successor = [[Abu al-Hasan as-Said al-Mutadid]] | death_date = December 4, 1242 |religion = [[Islam]] }} '''Abu Muhammad ar-Rashid Abd al-Wahid''' ({{lang-ar|أبو محمد الرشيد عبد الواحد بن المأمون}}; Abū Muḥammad Ar-Rashīd `Abd al-Wāḥid ibn Al-Mā'mūn; died 4 December 1242) was an [[Almohad Caliphate|Almohad]] rival caliph who reigned from 1232 until his death.
Abd al-Wahid succeeded his father [[Idris al-Ma'mun|Idris I]], who had died while marching against [[Yahya, Almohad Caliph|Yahya]], who was in control of the capital [[Marrakesh]]. His reign marked the beginning of the final fragmentation of the Almohad empire. He was not able to oust Yahya from Marrakesh, while the [[Kingdom of Tlemcen|Emir of Tlemcen]] become independent from 1236 (founding the [[Zayyanid dynasty]]), following the example of the [[Hafsid dynasty|Hafsid]] ruler [[Abu Zakariya Yahya]] in [[Tunisia]].
==Death== In 1242 he ordered his governor to fight another secession, that of the [[Marinid dynasty|Marinid]] [[Abu Yahya ibn Abd al-Haqq]], who had captured [[Fes]]. However, Abd al-Wahid was discovered drowned in a pool (or he died from a fall) in his palace in December of the same year. He was succeeded by his brother [[Abu al-Hasan as-Said al-Mutadid]].
==Sources== *Julien, Charles-André. ''Histoire de l'Afrique du Nord, des origines à 1830'', Payot, Paris, 1994.
