The '''Conspiracy Museum''' was a private exhibition of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] in the [[West End Historic District, Dallas, Texas|West End Historic District]] of [[downtown Dallas|downtown]] [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]], [[Texas]] ([[United States|USA]]).<ref name="dallj">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/28/us/dallas-journal-conspiracy-museum-draws-visitors-who-consider-the-plot-the-thing.html|title=Dallas Journal; Conspiracy Museum Draws Visitors Who Consider the Plot the Thing|accessdate=2008-03-27|date=1995-05-28|author=David Barboza|work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[Robert B. Cutler|R. B. Cutler]], self-described as an "assassinologist", opened the museum in 1995.<ref name="dallj"/>
The Conspiracy Museum was located across the street from the Kennedy Memorial in Dallas, Texas in the [[Katy Building]]. The museum was not limited in scope to [[John F. Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories|the conspiracy theories]] surrounding the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]], but it also covered [[Assassination of Robert F. Kennedy|Robert F. Kennedy]], [[Assassination of Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin Luther King Jr.]], [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Abraham Lincoln]], and [[Ted Kennedy]]'s [[Chappaquiddick incident]]. Cutler's argument was that all these conspiracies can be tied together.<ref name="all">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AASB&p_theme=aasb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAD979C6FDE7FD7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|title=Conspiracy Central|accessdate=2008-03-27|date=1995-06-05|author=James E. Garcia|work=The Austin American-Statesman}}</ref><ref name="thegre">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2003/11/22/wjfk22.xml|title='The Greatest Murder Mystery of all Time'|accessdate=2008-03-27|date=2003-11-22|author=David Rennie|work=The Telegraph | location=London}}</ref> The museum was often overlooked by visitors heading to the more well-known [[Sixth Floor Museum]].<ref name="overl">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED81DD266FEBEBE&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|title=Exploring|accessdate=2008-03-27|date=2001-03-15|author=Jay Web|work=The Dallas Morning News}}</ref><ref name="consp">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/TRAVEL/DESTINATIONS/11/21/jfk.museums.ap/|title=A Conspiracy -- Between JFK Museums|accessdate=2008-03-27|publisher=CNN|date=2003-11-21 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071210161919/http://www.cnn.com/2003/TRAVEL/DESTINATIONS/11/21/jfk.museums.ap/ |archivedate = December 10, 2007}}</ref>
The museum closed on December 30, 2006, having lost its lease.<ref>{{Cite episode |last=Goodwyn |first=Wade |authorlink=Wade Goodwyn|title=It's No Mystery: Rent Hike Kills Conspiracy Museum |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6600771 |series=Weekend Edition Saturday |serieslink=Weekend Edition |network=[[NPR]] |airdate=December 9, 2006 |transcript=Transcript |transcripturl=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=6600771 }}</ref> The building's owners announced that a [[Quiznos]] sandwich shop would take its place. Tom Bowden, the museum's president, said that the museum would re-locate to another part of the Katy Building or another location entirely and that detailed plans would be released.<ref name="close">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-30414053_ITM|title=JFK Conspiracy Museum Loses Its Space|accessdate=2008-03-27|date=2006-12-05|author=David Flick|work=The Dallas Morning News}}</ref>
